The social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region is recognized as an electronic means of payment.
The changes provide for the preservation of the travel privilege in public passenger transport.
From September 24, the procedure for organizing preferential travel of citizens using the social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region changes.
According to the press service of the government of Russia in the Ivanovo region, the changes provide for the preservation of the privilege to travel in public passenger transport and bring the scheme of mutual settlements on the social card in accordance with the requirements of the Federal Law No. 161 of the Federal Law "On the National Payment System".
At the same time, the social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region is recognized as an electronic means of payment.
Accordingly, the conditions of its use change.
Thus, the limit of replenishment is now set not in travel as before, but in the amount of money, with the preservation of winter and summer periods - in winter no more than 400 rubles, in summer - no more than 800 rubles for the current month.
Now the holders of the social card on the receipts issued in transport will need to monitor not the number of remaining trips, but the balance of funds.
The cost of preferential travel for citizens will be 1/2 of the tariff applicable to the carrier.
The remaining half of the cost of travel is reimbursed by the regional budget.
The schedule of replenishment of the social card with funds remains the same - in the period from the 24th of the previous month to the 23rd of the current month.
The new order of travel on the social map will have a number of advantages.
Thus, it is possible to keep a detailed record of the spending of money on the social card with accuracy to the kopecks.
In addition, it is possible to return credited, but unused funds.
We also add that the scheme of mutual settlements with carriers becomes transparent, since now half of the cost of travel is paid by the citizen, and the same amount is compensated by the budget of the carrier.
No commission will be charged when depositing funds on the card.
In turn, Vasily Silkin, Deputy Head of the Department of Roads and Transport of the Ivanovo Region, said that in 2014 there were more than 33 million trips in the region using a social card, in 2015 - almost 25 million trips.
In the regional budget for the provision of preferential travel of citizens using a social card, more than 470 million rubles are provided.
As of September 1, the amount of compensation for these purposes amounted to more than 312 million rubles.
During a 911 call, a teacher confesses to the murder of a friend.
During the 911 call, Shannon Lamb, a teacher at the university, told police that he had shot his girlfriend and that he needed staff to come to their home.
Lamb stressed that there was a “dog” in the house who was alive but probably upset, and said that the contacts of the family members of the deceased can be found on her phone.
Inside the house, police found Amy Prentiss's body and a note casually written by hand on a white sheet of linen paper: "I'm very sorry, I'd like to bring everything back, I loved Amy, and she's the only woman who ever loved me," the note said, according to authorities signed by Lamb.
There was no indication that Lamb, who led two online courses at the University of the State of Delta in Cleveland, Mississippi, had managed to drive 300 miles to the university campus by that time, where, according to police, he shot the respected history teacher Ethan Schmidt on the doorstep of his office.
The head of police at Delta State University, Lynn Baford, said the university learned of the shooting at 10:18 a.m.
He reported that Lamb made that true 911 call shortly afterwards.
By the end of the day, the victims will be one more: Lamb committed suicide as soon as the police surrounded him.
The day after the school shooting forced students and teachers to hide behind locked doors, authorities were still trying to piece together the motives that inspired Lamb.
The information shared by investigators in both corners of the state, as well as students and staff who knew him, helped draw a portrait of a talented but perhaps concerned teacher.
The students said they were looking forward to his classes.
Police in Gaultier, where Prentiss was killed, said he was not charged with violence or criminal charges.
Schmidt himself included Lamb in the book he wrote, in which he expressed gratitude for the "beautiful people" with whom he intersected in his teaching life.
Both of them taught at the Faculty of Social Sciences and History, which has 17 teachers, and many students attended lectures of both.
At the same time, there were some prerequisites for problems.
One student who spoke well about Lamb, Brandon Beavers, reported that he also seemed alarmed and nervous, “as if something was wrong with him.”
Another student, Michael Sykes, reported that Lamb told him at the end of the 2014-15 school year about how he struggled with stress.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University to grant him sick leave, saying he had some health problems.
This year he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes in university admissions meant that the doctorate, which Lamb had worked so hard to obtain, would not guarantee him an automatic teaching position.
University President William Laforge said he knew nothing about the conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but “obviously Mr. Lamb had something on his mind.”
These are questions that Lamb will no longer be able to answer.
Police attacked Lamb's trail after his escape from campus as he was heading back to Mississippi from Arkansas.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb shot himself with a 38-caliber handgun in the backyard of the house, a mile south of his parents' home in the suburb of Greenville, Mississippi, Washington County Coroner Metel Johnson said.
His engine-powered car was still standing on the driveway.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb came to the house, although, according to Johnson, she believes that he knew the people who lived in it.
Lamb grew up in those parts.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3,500 students in the city with a population of about 12,000, in 2009 and taught geography and pedagogy.
He received his doctorate in pedagogical sciences in the spring of the same year.
One of Lamb’s longtime friends described him as a smart, charismatic and cheerful person.
Carla Hareston said she was 15 and Lamb was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
She and her friends were in high school, and he was a cool older guy who for several years tried to teach her how to play the guitar.
In those years, he enjoyed success with women.
All the girls were melting when he was around,” says Hareston, now 40, who lives in Jackson, a suburb of Brandon.
Lamb and Prentiss had probably met for some time at the time of the events.
During a 911 call, Lamb said, “I killed my wife,” but there is no record of their marriage being registered.
The couple had a dog named Lightning, who lived with them in Gauthier in a brick house, the opposite side of which overlooks the canal.
According to police, the dog is fine.
Prentice’s ex-husband, Sean O’Steen, reported that they divorced 15 years ago but remained friends, and that they have a daughter who is now 19 years old.
"She's totally depressed," O'Steen said of her daughter.
She and her mother were good friends.
O'Steen said he hadn't met Lamb, but heard from his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and playing blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail both performed at the same summer festival three years ago.
They played together at concerts from time to time.
O'Steen said his daughter was writing music and singing.
Prentiss was a nurse and worked online for various companies.
Mike Schaffer, a bartender and co-ordinator of entertainment programs at the dimly lit bar The Julep Room in the suburb of Gauthier, said he last saw Lamb and Prentiss on the evening of September 5, when Lamb finished playing guitar and harmonica for a few visitors.
Nothing suspicious was observed.
“Just a happy couple,” he said.
We were laughing and laughing at each other.
I mean, they were both very witty.
Schmidt, a deceased teacher, conducted seminars for freshmen and specialized in the history of Native Americans and colonial America, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English teacher at the same school.
He was married and had three small children.
He studied at the University of Kansas in Emporia and was president of the Student Fraternity and Student Self-Government.
On the University of the Delta campus in Cleveland on Tuesday evening, about 900 people, including university professors, staff, students and community members, participated in the candlelight memorial ceremony.
Schmidt's wife Liz and brother Jeff Schmidt also attended the ceremony, during which the university choir sang Bright Morning Star and Amazing Grace.
Classes will resume on Wednesday.
“We are trying to get our students back,” Laforge said.
The crisis is over.
Today is recovery day.
Amy and Rogelio Solis report from Cleveland, Mississippi.
The report helped to prepare the authors of the Associated Press Emily Vagster Pettus in Greenville, Mississippi, and Rebecca Santana in New Orleans.
The material was edited in connection with a police statement that Lamb's call came to 911 after Schmidt's murder, and in connection with the fact that although Lamb spoke of Prentice as his wife when he called 911, the information that they were married was not confirmed.
