8 Poll Results That Show Donald Trump Is Not Joking
Some tried to label him as a provocateur.
Others dismissed him as a joke.
Some people want a scandal.
But while some Republicans are trying to shake up Donald Trump’s high position in the polls, they haven’t succeeded (yet).
Ten of the last 11 national polls have shown Donald Trump’s advantage in double digits, and some are beginning to seriously ask what this means for a real estate tycoon in terms of chances of getting a nomination.
Of course, this is only the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this means Trump has a chance to nominate the Republican Party.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry gave up his advantage to the gaining popularity of Herman Kane, none of whom won a single state in the process of nomination.
And there are many reasons why he would fight in the general election.
But outside groups, such as Jeb Bush’s “Political Activity Supercommittee” and the economic conservative “Growth Club” group, recognize Trump’s unrelenting strength and start pulling out their dollars to overturn him.
Here are some survey figures that suggest that a real estate tycoon is not just an intermediate phase:
The ratings of sympathies for Trump turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a poll at Monmouth University found that only two out of 10 Republicans were positive about the real estate tycoon.
By mid-July, it was 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, it was 52%.
Now six out of 10 Republicans are positive about Donald Trump.
About 3 out of 10 say they have a negative opinion.
And all these indicators prevail in the initial stages.
A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found that 60 percent of Republicans there are positive about Trump.
Two-thirds of those who voted for the GOP would vote for Trump as a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they were either “enthusiastic” or “satisfying” if Trump became a candidate.
Only two out of 10 say they would be “disturbed” if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson generates about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent say they would be “enthusiastic” against 40 percent of those who say the same about Trump).
Next in level of excitement?
Marco Rubio, who has only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republicans say they will be “dissatisfied” or “disappointed” if the establishment’s favorite Jeb Bush becomes a candidate.
Most Republicans don’t see Trump’s temperament as a problem.
While Trump has been widely criticized for his bragging and insults, 52 percent of Republican-facing voters across the country think the tycoon has the right temperament to be president, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll conducted on Monday.
The same figure appears at the country’s first closed meeting in Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he has the same man who could be the commander-in-chief, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he’s not the kind of person who can be effective in office, and nearly six in 10 independent voters say his temperament isn’t right for the White House, according to ABC/Post reports.
Republicans are getting used to this idea.
When they put on their connoisseurs’ hats, Republican voters think Trump is serious.
When asked who the most likely winner of the GOP nomination was, four out of 10 said Trump was the favorite, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
This is no longer the case when four out of 10 bet Jeb Bush at the end of July.
Full disclosure: GOP voters didn’t have the right magic crystal before.
At the same time, in the last cycle, four out of 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry as the most likely candidate, while only 28 percent supported a possible candidate, Mitt Romney.
However, it shows that many GOP voters find Trump’s campaign convincing.
Even if the Republicans were to rally around another candidate, Trump is still ahead of everyone else.
Some experts point out that such a scattering is likely to be Trump’s advantage, and at the same time the non-Trump supporters are evenly distributed among the supporting more than a dozen other candidates.
But a survey conducted by Monmouth University in early September shows that in a hypothetical one-on-one competition between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always gets the support of the majority.
He ahead of Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and finally Rand Paul, John Kesich and Chris Christie by 33 points.
He has a draw with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate who gets around him?
Ben Carson beat the businessman by 19 points in a one-on-one hypothetical competition.
Just over half of Donald Trump’s supporters say they have changed their mind.
A new CBS/NYT poll on Tuesday shows that only more than half of Trump-backed voters say they are confident in their votes.
Obviously, a lot can happen and change the situation, and no one can really say that he will never change his mind.
46% say they leave the door open to other candidates.
Still, Trump’s toughest competition at the moment is with outsider colleague neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who say they’ve changed their mind are likely to choose Trump.
Six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Since Donald Trump two months ago called immigrants from Mexico “rapists” in his campaign speech, the topic of immigration has become the most topical in conversations in 2016.
Some worry that Trump’s posing will distract key Hispanic voters from the Republican Party and prevent rebranding.
But according to an ABC/Post poll conducted on Monday, six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So as long as immigration attracts widespread attention, it seems that Donald Trump will remain in the same position.
Disappointment with the government is gaining momentum.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson now count on the support of about half of Republican voters, mainly because of their status as outsiders.
Six out of 10 Republicans on Monday in a new ABC/Post poll say they want a political outsider rather than a man with government experience.
And they are also offended by Washington.
A poll by Des Moines Register/Bloomberg in Iowa two weeks ago showed that three out of four Republicans in Iowa were disappointed with Republicans in Congress, with 54 percent “dissatisfied” and 21 percent “outraged.”
