Metcash launches grassroots initiative to counter Aldi’s attack
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from the onslaught of Aldi in South Australia and Western Australia.
A bottom-up food supplier has launched a campaign to protect IGA retailers’ market share in South Australia and Western Australia in light of Aldi’s upcoming $700 million infusion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two wholesale warehouses and the first of 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening ties with local food suppliers and promoting the IGA brand through marketing in leading media and social media and at Adelaide Show events.
The campaign is joined by IGA retailers and suppliers, such as ice cream maker Simmo's from Dunsborough, which offers tastings at IGA stores, and shop owners selling discounted tickets to South Australia Football League matches to regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details of its protection strategy on September 29, the day that this wholesale supplier of food, spirits and household goods will hold its annual investor strategy day.
In South Australia and Western Australia, IGA stores account for almost 30% of all Metcash stores and show higher profitability than the Metcash IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South and Western Australia are known to adhere to the usual routes, so the market here is more favorable for IGA retailers than in the states of New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 percent in the South and 24 percent in WA compared to about 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will cede 5 percent of the food market in these two states within 12 months of opening its first stores, taking the sales volume from all the players present, but mainly from independent retailers.
In a report published this week, Tom Kirat, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, estimates that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year, and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
The forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi next year will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA, achieving sales of $ 500 million and $ 600 million in these markets respectively.
