What happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates?
There will be an increase in rates, and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will grow, and the economy will plunge into recession.
That's what we know.
What we do not know is how long it will take before the offensive, and how long it will continue.
For the economy in particular, history does not explain much about time.
The recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike and by as much as 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s toughness in raising rates often, but not always, determines the response of the economy and financial assets.
That’s why the US central bank administration insists that investors should not focus on when it will start raising rates, but on how long it will take to adapt.
There are a lot of variables in the game.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the fuss about raising rates is exaggerated.
“The first rate hike by the Federal Reserve with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal of the end of the era of ‘cheap money,’” said Julian Jessop, chief international economics officer at Capital Economics, in his commentary to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect that the gradual return of interest rates in the US to more normal, but still low levels will be a seismic impulse that many fear.
This does not mean, however, that there will be no consequences.
Here’s a look at how some areas of the economy might have reacted depending on historical trends:
As the market has seen over the past month or so, the expectation of an increase in rates may lead to volatility for some time.
When raising the rate, however, the consequences are usually not so dramatic.
“It doesn’t look like stock earnings will slow down 12-24 months after the first jump, which again probably reflects a delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve.
More specifically, the market over the past approximately 35 years is more likely to change sharply - about 14 percent - in the direction of raising rates, remains fairly flat for 250 days after that (average growth of 2.6 percent), then, after 500 days, returns to normal with an average return of 14.4 percent over the last six cycles, according to a recent analysis conducted by Aset'en Doll, chief specialist in strategy.
Deutsche says the result for securities tends not to immediately become more pronounced at the rate hike stage, and stock earnings are beginning to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but increases in rates often play a part in them.
In this case, the Federal Reserve is placed in conditions that did not exist before and can accelerate the recession.
Basically, the gross domestic product will be at almost its lowest point in the lifetime of the increased rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 cases raising rates since 1950, only twice the nominal annual GDP was below 4.5 percent.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it is long-term, with it holding at just 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates against such an unstable economic background can be risky and raises the question “whether it will be different this time,” Deutsche said.
Market participants are preparing to raise rates by the Federal Reserve all year round, with their eyes fixed on the meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategy experts and economists believe that the FOMC could approve a rate hike at this meeting, futures trading shows only a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, since 1950, all cycles of rate hikes to date have been in a supercycle of increasing financial leverage at a GDP that overlaps the pre-recession peaks very quickly after the start of the recovery,” the report said.
By contrast, it was an extremely slow recovery after the worst recession in a selected period.
The current cycle at the moment is the longest that the Federal Reserve has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, it only lasts 74 months and is not over yet.
Fixed income has also become volatile while the market expects an increase in rates, and this scenario is somewhat similar to that implemented for stocks.
The fundamental difference is that for bonds, the effect will come faster than for stocks, when the Federal system changes the strategic course.
In the case of bonds, it seems that the yield changes the vector immediately after the first increase/decrease in the cycle.
At the end of the rate hike cycle, bond yields immediately fall,” Deutsche said.
Strategy experts from Charles Schwab believe that raising rates will lead to the fact that the yield levels of long-term and short-term bonds will converge, making the curve more flat.
High-yield bonds often behave better in such a climate, although “we are still afraid of yield fluctuations,” says study by Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the expected results of the Federal system’s policies.
“In addition to strengthening the dollar and falling inflation expectations, there are signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of a tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Interest rates on short-term loans have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have expanded, volatility has increased - all the characteristics of the market with the tightening of the Federal system policy.
Generally speaking, companies running their main business in the United States will benefit from an increase in interest rates, and local products will become more attractive.
International companies with a lot of debt will be worse off as the rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market space, and their debt more expensive in the financial space.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks are more effective than the market within three months of the initial rate hike,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for clients.
Companies with stable financial standings bypassed those with unstable standings as a result of each rate increase in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital returns as well as low volatility stocks also showed better performance than low-quality stocks, an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt will be a big issue.
Companies with high floating-rate debt will lose the most, according to Goldman.
In addition to purely exchange-traded transactions, consumers will benefit from the rising dollar.
Investors could also see profits through higher returns, although experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
