Vangelis Meimarakis has been part of the center-right governments for years, which leftists believe have led the country to a financial crisis.
Now that he has become the interim leader of the New Democracy party, he is challenging Tsipras.
A few days before the election, he met with journalist Euronews.
Euronews: Mr. Maymarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronews: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat, yielding to the SYRIZA coalition, but now, according to polls, the New Democracy has equaled it in popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Meimarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot in January last year.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and prospects for economic growth.
Now the country again has a budget deficit and a high unemployment rate.
The investors left because Mr. Tsipras drove them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what was promised to what actually happened.
Daily life became noticeably worse than in January, when the situation improved, and this affected most Greek citizens.
Euronews: But you say that if you win the election, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
Vangelis Meimarakis: The fact is that, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is no coincidence that in all other countries where rescue programmes have been or are still in operation, political forces and all ruling parties have come together to implement the programme on which they have agreed without renouncing their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party voted in favour of the agreement between Mr Tsipras and the creditors of the country.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you implement this agreement, or will you try to change it, at least in part?
Vangelis Meimarakis: In fact, we voted to move Greece on the European path because we have a good idea of what the disastrous consequences of leaving the EU would be.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All this would have been lost had there not been a treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures are the result of how Mr. Tsipras negotiated.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government in its first year in power wants to restore order, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then I am sure that all the commitments made, which cannot be fulfilled because of what leads to a recession, can again be negotiated, but only after a certain time.
It would be wrong to believe that in the first year of the new agreement, we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect full implementation of the agreement.
If we want to restore their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed upon, while continuing to take advantage of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the negotiations, the Tsipras government did not present any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we found out when discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
Let me give you an example of farmers’ income.
We have explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that the Tsipras ministers never spoke about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were not prepared and poorly informed, and therefore unsuccessfully negotiated and concluded a failed agreement.
Euronews: If you win the election, you will soon be at the same table with Mr Juncker, Hollande, Mrs Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them be different from what your predecessor, Antonis Samaras, told them?
Vangelis Meimarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that until the end of 2014, we tried to implement the 2012 agreement in the best way, bypassing the sharp corners that it had.
We are moving forward with reforms.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in extraordinary circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price that the Greek government was pleased with.
I was the Speaker of Parliament at the time, and I was able to agree on the views of the three parliamentary groups that constituted the government majority at the time.
And despite their serious ideological differences over key bills, we had a working parliament, and this was in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations that took place outside.
And we managed to bring the country to a normal situation that would continue to improve if the process had not been interrupted by the early general elections that resulted from the December presidential elections.
Euronews: In recent weeks, a mass flow of refugees has been moving through Greece.
What do you think about this situation and the reaction of the European countries to which these people are striving?
Vangelis Meimarakis: The refugee crisis is a time-bomb that we have to deal with after winning the election.
And the reason is that the SYRIZA government has not acted in this situation as it should have.
In such matters, you should act ahead of time, because if the problem catches up with you, then only emergency measures remain.
And that's exactly the situation we're in now.
Even the interim government that replaced SYRIZA did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am confident that these actions of the interim government, which is provided with valuable assistance by the President of the Republic, who called for an EU summit, will allow to find a solution.
We need to see how many refugees will be able to leave the country, and note that refugees are not illegal immigrants.
They are victims of the war in Syria, victims of some extraordinary events that happened to them.
This issue has a deeply humanitarian aspect, and we will stick to the position that European politicians must take in this new situation.
The relevant decision should be taken at the EU summit, and the United Nations should be involved.
We also need better coordination, more effective border controls and refugee reception centres.
We also need to make effective use of the economic assistance we receive from the EU in order to be able to tackle this pressing problem.
Euronews: Mr. Maymarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you.
