Kiev tore apart the atomic union.
Kiev officially formalized the refusal of Ukraine to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnitsky NPP.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday with a second attempt still voted for the termination of the agreement with Moscow.
Arrangements for the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but the project could not be started.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law cancelling the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth blocks at the Khmelnitsky NPP.
The draft law submitted by the government was implemented only from the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the required minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted for the draft.
The Khmelnytsky NPP laid down under the USSR under the original project was supposed to have four power units of 1 GW with VVER-type reactors, but only two were built.
Negotiations with Moscow on completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2010, in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the blocks would have to be built on credit from the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to close relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing its refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant and the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only sphere where the relations have been preserved is the purchase of fuel in the Russian Federation for the existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants (provided about half of the electricity generation in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NPP Energoatom has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
The plans to complete the Khmelnitsky NPP with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been definitively abandoned: back in 2014, Kiev announced negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS.
