The parties were given mandates.
Yesterday, the election commission of Nizhny Novgorod summed up the results of the elections to the city Duma in the municipal district, distributing 12 deputy mandates, played out on party lists.
Traditionally, many complaints about violations during the elections were heard from representatives of the CPRF, accusing the electorate of “covering up falsifications”.
Opposition comments were not accepted.
At the same time, the electorate refused the Communists of Russia party to organize a referendum on the abolition of the fee for the repair of apartment buildings.
The city electorate officially presented the results of the elections in the pride of Nizhny Novgorod for the municipal constituency.
In total, 1.03 million people were included in the voters' lists in Nizhny Novgorod, 746.7 thousand ballots were issued for voting in the precinct commissions, and 268,000 voters voted in the elections.
More than 11,700 ballots were declared invalid and 24 were lost.
Yesterday, 12 mandates were distributed among political parties, depending on the votes they received.
According to the lists of "United Russia", six deputies' seats in pride rely on Dmitry Svatkovsky, Dmitry Krasnov, Vasily Shupranov, Elizaveta Solonchenko, Vyacheslav Rasteryaev and Igor Nagorny.
The only mandate of the LDPR was given to party leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
Two CPRF mandates are distributed between Vladimir Bulanov and State Duma deputy Alexander Tarnaev.
The three mandates of "Fair Russia" are given to Alexander Razumovsky, Igor Bogdanov and Mikhail Shalyugin.
Now, within five days, these candidates have to decide whether they will work as deputies in the city council: in the event of a waiver of the mandate, he goes to the next candidate on the party list.
Chairman of the Election Committee Alexander Makeev told the members of the commission that he introduces the duty to "send telegrams to Zhirinovsky and others" for the rejection of mandates.
When approving the protocol on the results of the elections, the representatives of the CPRF reported multiple violations.
Leonid Krasnokutsky, a member of the electoral commission with the right of deliberative vote from the Communist Party of Ukraine, proposed not to recognize the results of voting in four districts No. 21-24, recalling that by order of the head of the administration of the Sormov district, the entrance to the administration building, where the four district commissions were located, was closed.
For a long time, neither the deputies of the State Duma, nor the candidates themselves, nor the observers could go inside, and a resonant scandal with the storming of the doors of the district administration was shown on television.
At the meetings of the district commissions, all observers and members of the commissions with the right of deliberative vote had the opportunity to attend.
Their head stopped access only when the vote was over and the precinct commissions had not yet come to submit their ballots.
This was done in order to prevent various provocations.
"Then the chapter was corrected, and at all meetings interested persons could be present," - said Natalia Andryushina, a member of the mountains of the Electoral Committee.
The Communists objected that in the blocked administration building for more than four hours illegally detained the deputy of the assembly of the region Lyudmila Aristov, about which a statement was sent to the investigative committee.
The opposition was also outraged that a number of UICs began sealing the urns at 6-7 a.m. on election day, putting ballots for early voting in them.
At the same time, the members of the commissions with the right to a deliberative vote and observers were not notified, so they came to the beginning of the elections at 8 am.
Communists believe that in the morning before the opening of polling stations, ballots could be thrown into the urns uncontrollably.
However, the election commission, which has already considered more than 124 complaints for various reasons, according to Alexander Makeev, did not find any violations with the throws of unaccounted ballots.
The members of the commission did not support the proposal of their colleague from "Fair Russia" Maria Popova through the lezzebirkom to come out with amendments to the regional legislation to clearly set the time of opening the envelopes with ballots of early voting, which then fall into the urn.
"On your own initiative, contact at least the CEC," Alexander Makeev advised Mrs. Popova.
At the end of the meeting, CPRF member Sergei Samokhin fell on the chairman with loud accusations, shouting that the electorate ignored dozens of complaints and covered forgery in the elections.
"You are not here at a rally, be careful to declare!" - offended the chairman of the election committee.
In the end, the protocol was approved almost unanimously.
Until September 27, the electorate must approve the general results of the elections, after which the first meeting of the city Duma of Nizhny Novgorod of the sixth convocation will be appointed within three weeks.
In addition to determining the results of the elections, the city election commission refused the political party "Communists of Russia" to register an initiative group to hold a local referendum.
According to the documents, the parties were going to put two questions to the discussion of Nizhny Novgorod residents: whether they agree with the fact that the fees for the repair of apartment buildings should be "immediately canceled", and tariffs for housing and communal services "freeze until 2020".
However, the lawyer of the Duma Irina Maslova explained that the appeal of the “Communists of Russia” is contrary to the legislation.
FedEx’s revenue is mixed, down forecasts for 2016.
FedEx reported disappointing results in the last quarter, and the delivery service giant reduced its annual profit forecast due to falling demand for freight services and rising costs in its ground transportation division.
The company also said it plans to hire about 55,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At the same time last year, FedEx announced that it would hire 50,000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell about 2.5 percent in pre-traded trading 45 minutes before the exchange opened on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it plans to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 in the fiscal year ending next May, 20 cents less than the previous forecast.
Analysts assumed $10.84 according to the FactSet review.
The forecast is falling despite an average 4.9 percent rate hike, which will come into effect on January 4, and a rise in ground handling fees for heavy or bulky goods, which begins in November.
The company said it still plans to increase revenue compared to last year due to cost cuts, increased gross revenue and growth in online trading.
Fred Smith, chairman and CEO, said the company was “working stably with weak economic conditions, especially in manufacturing and global trade, as compared to the forecast.”
Plans to hire workers during the holidays were announced the day after a competitor, UPS, announced that they plan to hire an additional 95,000 employees, roughly the same as they hired last year.
For the quarter, which ended August 31, FedEx earned $ 692 million, 6 percent more than a year earlier.
Revenue per share was $2.42, close to the forecast of an average of $2.44 per share, conducted by Zacks Investment Research in a survey of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased by 5% to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts surveyed by Zacks estimated $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a downturn in the international express transportation sector, leading to a lack of growth in gross income in its express transportation division.
However, the boom in online shopping has dramatically improved results in FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, ground transportation revenues increased by 29%, but operating revenues remained largely unchanged due to increased costs of large shipments and self-insurance.
The express transportation division received higher incomes due to higher base rates, while in the freight sector, incomes fell due to higher labor costs.
In pre-traded trading, about an hour before the stock market opened, FedEx’s shares fell by $3.85 or 2.5 percent to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the June 11 record.
At the most anticipated meeting in a few years, Federal Reserve leaders will spend two days this week at a 27-foot Honduran redwood table, deciding whether it’s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At one end of the richly decorated two-story meeting room, a wall image of the United States will hang over them.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the country above all others.
The Central Bank received a double order from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal system have acknowledged that there is a third unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And this third order could be an unknown factor in a near-foreseen decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the US economy is ready to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data shows robust economic growth, recent shocks in global financial markets may deter already cautious Federal system leaders from adding volatility by raising the base rate on federal funds — even by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important thing to consider,” said Lindsay M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise the stakes, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further,” she said.
There is no consensus on what will be done in the Federal Reserve, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted interest rate hikes this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal system to refrain from doing so, with the key indicator showing only about a 30 percent chance of a rapid recovery.
This could lead to a fall in the stock market if the Federal system raises the rate, provided that decision makers do not soften the blow by promising that the next increase will not be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,598.85.
The take-off was triggered by expectations that the policy makers of the Federal system would leave the bet this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It will be a surprise if the Federal system raises rates at this point in time,” he said.
If the Federal Reserve does, “they will have to go a long way in approving their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they don’t panic.”
Other experts objected that raising the rate could calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the federal system seemed inclined to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although the growth of new jobs slowed in August, labor market growth was stable this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and almost at what the Federal System considers full employment.
The increase in wages shows signs of acceleration.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank’s 2% annual target, the Federal system’s leadership said the key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy “can handle higher rates, and needs them, given the shrinking labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The average Dow Jones index for industrial stocks fell as much as 16% from a record high in May, as investors feared a slowdown in China's economy could hamper global growth.
The market partially regained its position this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10% below its high May value.
For the leadership of the Federal Reserve, market outrage further complicates the difficult calculations of the timing of the interest rate hike.
“In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, they would have started to twist the nuts at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve employee.
Now, according to his forecasts, they will wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
“There is a great deal of uncertainty about what the consequences might be for the U.S. economy, and they have little to no reliable data since the recent events in China,” he said.
The health of the global economy is not a major concern of the Federal system and should not be taken into account in these decisions.
But essentially, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint from then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could “muffle” its monetary expansion has caused shocks in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined, it would be expected that the leaders of the Federal Reserve would not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the world economy.
Their decision-making process is “art rather than science,” said Zachary Carabell, head of Envestnet Inc., a company that deals with global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Laker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that “in the history of the Federal Reserve, there have been instances of overreaction to financial market movements that seem unrelated to economic principles.”
Lacker, a voting member of the influential Federal Open Market Committee who insisted on raising the rate, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia has led the Federal System to lower its base rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the limited identifiable implications for growth in the United States," Lacker said.
A year later, the leaders of the Federal system canceled these cuts.
The Federal Reserve should put stability first only in times of major crises such as the 2008 market crash,” said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the interest rate committee at the Bank of England.
The last panic did not come close to this level, he said.
“You wouldn’t want to be in a situation where you’re scared of rising rates because markets are experiencing a shock,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for the World Economy.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don’t think they should be ahead of the curve.
