Low-obesity diabetics may benefit from obesity surgery
The beneficial effect after obesity surgery in people with low-obesity type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say that diabetics with low obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
“Death rates don’t show up right away,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity surgery, who wrote about the new study in a column by JAMA Surgery editor.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Bariatric surgery has proven to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes over several years, but the main studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal at a value from 18.5 to 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass surgery and sleeve-type gastrectomy - with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with low obesity.
The mean BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year of study.
At the same time, BMI in those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and partially - 28%.
In the group that received medication, for comparison, a complete cure for diabetes was observed in only 1%, and a partial cure was observed in only about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors said.
The researchers also controlled blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is better kept below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But the best glycemic control measures, reflected by good levels of hemoglobin A1c, did not reduce mortality rates over five years, according to study leader Dr. Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
In the fifth year, compared to the group that had a sleeve gastroctomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (7.4 vs 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs 2.1%), and was also closer to complete remission of diabetes (46.9% vs 16.7%).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of surgery in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone of the College of Medicine in Phoenix, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study for obese people who chose bariatric intervention, the likelihood of dying within 15 years was about 29% lower compared to the group that used more traditional methods.
Despite the fact that the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this encourages people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in such a procedure.
“The report is very important here because it states that such surgery is safe in a low BMI group where there is no increased risk of death or kidney disease,” she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient’s BMI falls in the range of between 27 to 30.
“I think we’ve been waiting too long to get people to take it seriously,” she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse it.
