The lack of such stories is striking, especially considering how desperate men’s need for honesty has become, now more than ever, with the suicide rate among young men at its highest in 15 years.
In 2013, it was the single largest cause of death for men between the ages of 20 and 45 in the United Kingdom, and men are three times more likely to die than women.
In an effort to understand the problem, Campaign Against Unhappy Life declared 2015 the Year of Men to challenge a culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the center of this battle to take on this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 university students showing symptoms of depression found that if a patient has a sufficiently large number of friends "in a normal mood", the chances of healing are doubled.
Similarly, for those who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halves the chance of mental disorders.
But, of course, in order for friendship to work, first of all, it must be.
In an era where communication is managed by social media, where style is preferred to content, response speed is often valued more than meaningful contact.
Our digital life doubles the need to seem strong, fun-loving, and successful, even when in reality loneliness reigns.
Such superficial success depends on what psychologists call external values - money, image, social status, entirely at the expense of internal values, our inner desire for personal growth and friendship, which has a greater impact on our mental health.
And, as a billionaire video game creator recently noticed, money is not really buying any more happiness.
The advantage of Friends is that they draw attention to it.
Each of the characters was determined not by their work, but rather by the personality that manifested itself in communication with friends.
Joey’s humor and Chandler’s constant hugs, moments of watching football on comfortable chairs, Ross’ sighs at Rachel – all come from the understanding that men can feel it, even if they often refrain from fully exploring their feelings.
