Economics <0xE2><0x80><0x95> Nobel laureate: globalization
The processes of globalization should have contributed to reducing inequalities in the world.
In fact, the situation is different, the difference in incomes of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, says Eric Maskin, chief researcher at the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Solutions at HSE, winner of the 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics.
Over the past twenty years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between countries have become increasingly open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for emerging economies.
"And these predictions have largely come true," Muskin emphasizes.
For example, China and India have seen a significant increase in GDP per capita.
However, not everything is so cheerful.
Globalization was expected to reduce the gap between the “rich” and the “poor” in poor countries, which is manifested in large income inequality, or rather wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article “Why Global Markets Haven’t Reduced Inequality in Emerging Economies,” published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and cited by HSE.
Together with the economist, Harvard University professor Michael Kremer, Eric Maskin developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why the income gap in poor countries increases as globalization grows.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Muskin allocates four skill levels – A and B for rich countries, C and D – for poor countries.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries do not have enough qualifications to cooperate with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And if C-level workers from poor countries have their salaries increased by cooperating with B-level workers from the rich, then D-level workers do not feel the growth or their salaries fall at all.
The resulting effect is that the internationalization of production will contribute to widening the wage gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and, accordingly, to increasing inequalities.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
It explains why globalization has led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, a full-time professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision-Making, head of the mathematics department at HSE.
And like any powerful theory, I am sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this field.
The solution to the problem, according to Eric Maskin, is to improve the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the funds for this, and companies are disadvantaged to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private funds can play a significant role, according to Maskin.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no way calls for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bearing fruit in the form of GDP growth of countries.
Derbent: The living connection of time.
Derbent - one of the oldest cities in Russia - in September celebrates its 2000th anniversary.
The program of festive events includes a festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and a fair in the style of past times, an exhibition of Derbent carpets and Open Temples Day, a historical and musical show "2000 years in two hours" and excursions to the reconstructed Peter I Museum.
Medieval stones of Naryn-Kala fortress, ancient Arab inscriptions on the walls, narrow streets and palace gardens - all this seems to have come down from the pages of "A Thousand and One Nights".
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has survived in its place since ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, Khazar Khaganate and the Golden Horde.
The age of the Eastern Platans, which grow in the courtyard of the Derbent Juma Mosque, is equal to several centuries.
These powerful plants are under the protection of the All-Russian program "Trees - wildlife monuments".
The shadow of the scattered crowns saves pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
The visitor of the mosque will pour aromatic tea and treat Dagestan delicacies - honey figs, perch, mushmula, miracle cakes, airan and sweets.
In Derbent, from time immemorial, large samovars have been used to drink tea to numerous guests at once.
The inscription above the entrance to the Juma Mosque says that the building was built in the year 115 Hijra.
That is, in 733 according to the Gregorian calendar.
It is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is striking in scope and solemnity: the arcades of domes and vaults rest on square columns and are illuminated by the rays of the sun from tiny windows.
The content and breeding of pigeons is a traditional hobby of the inhabitants of Derbent.
Poultry owners put doves in yards, under trees, in attics.
An exciting sight is the ascent into the sky of a pack of white pigeons, similar to flashes of festive fireworks.
In order to defend against the enemy, the ancient Persians blocked the Caspian Gate with a double stone wall.
Walking 500 meters into the sea, this structure closed the harbour of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best-preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets in Derbent were woven in the 5th century, and to this day the technology of this unique craft has remained almost unchanged.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets are sold for every taste - strips of wool, cotton or felt of all colors and shades, with a pile and without it, with a complex ornament and a whimsical border.
The construction of the city began with magals - neighborhoods with one-story stone buildings.
Over the years, the mosquitoes have hardly changed.
Only satellite dishes, air conditioners on the walls and street lights remind you that you are not in the medieval, but in a modern city.
In the old part of the city preserved the details of the water supply, built by the Persians about a thousand years ago.
To this day, ancient sources have reached, in which local residents still collect water today.
Many derbents prefer ordinary tap water to water from proven historical fountains.
In Derbent was one of the centers of pottery crafts.
Irrigation and painted vases, dishes, jugs, cups were valued throughout the Caucasus.
Hands of potters and now produce wonderful ceramic products for both practical and souvenir purposes.
On the days of holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under a tight rope, on which students of the Republican School of Circus Art perform.
The history of amazing and risky craftsmanship dates back several centuries.
A new trend - among cable car drivers, you can increasingly see girls.
In the premises of the former Maiden's Bath today there is a museum "Culture and life of the Ancient Derbent".
Previously, unmarried girls and brides were washed here, accompanied by girlfriends, and now anyone can see the vaulted dome hall, hot and cold pools, which have gone into the past bathing accessories.
The majority of Derbent houses have hot water, but baths and steam rooms are just as popular these days as they were in the old days.
The benefits of heating the body with steam are written in ancient books.
After the bath, the blood improves, the muscles lose fatigue, the body acquires flexibility and ease.
The festival "Commonwealth", which takes place on the territory of Naryn-Kala fortress, is attended by ethnologists from many districts of Dagestan.
Participants in national costumes dance, play folk melodies, sing songs of the peoples of the Caucasus and treat visitors with delicious homemade cheese.
Kirkhlyar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid their heads for Islam.
It is one of the most revered complexes for Muslims of the North Caucasus.
The yellowed sarcophagi are carved from solid stone blocks and are oriented, as is customary with the Arabs, along the west-east axis.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubov cut and shave clients in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
The hairdresser has been in this place for many years.
Receptions of the cyrillic craft are passed down from generation to generation.
At the same time, the Yakubov brothers can make not only traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old Town there is a house in which the exiled decembrist writer Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinsky lived.
Having learned the Turkic language and collected ethnographic material, he described Derbent in the first third of the 19th century with his ancient monuments, life and everyday life of the citizens.
Chaikhana is a traditional club of the East, where only tea and homemade pastries are served.
Men come here to quench thirst, chat with friends and solve some work problems.
As in previous times, it is not recommended for women to cross the threshold of teahouses.
Derbent dance ensemble "Caspian" was created three years ago, but has already managed to take part in events of the republican and Russian level.
The soloists of the ensemble rehearse every day, perfecting the folk Avar, Dargin, Tata, Armenian dances.
With the onset of the evening, when the noise subsides and street lights are lit, locals sit on benches near houses with protruding terraces.
Typically, derbents discuss household issues.
But on the eve of the anniversary, they are increasingly recalling episodes of the unique history of their city, which influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
