The Green Tribunal was quick to crack down.
Typical situation: four officials stand in front of Judge Svatanter Kumar’s desk, hearing his claims to the work done.
The court is not satisfied with the quality of your work.
We didn’t give you a 110-page order to make fun of it,” Kumar says.
If one more brick is laid, we will order the demolition of all existing buildings.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (NGT), a judicial body established in 2010 to stop the rapid pollution that has accompanied the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal managed to consider more than 10,000 lawsuits related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological development, toxic waste and dam construction.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to discontinue construction leading to pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in the less than 60 years since the declaration of independence of industrial development, India has grown from a virgin jungle country to one of the most overcrowded and polluted countries in the world.
Particularly acute is the problem in large metropolises, where the development of infrastructure does not keep pace with rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from enterprises and households, and few remaining residential areas are cut down for construction by new residential quarters.
